The <b>Ocellated Thrasher</b> (<i>Toxostoma ocellatum</i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mimidae" title="Mimidae" class="mw-redirect">Mimidae</a> family. It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to the highlands of south-central <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitats</a> are dry scrubland and open oak and pine woodland between 1500 and 3000&nbsp;m above sea-level.
It is about 30&nbsp;cm long. Its upperparts are brown while the underparts are white with round black spots. The outer tail-feathers have narrow white tips. It has a long musical <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_song" title="Bird song" class="mw-redirect">song</a> with phrases of two or three notes.
